[[File:GenerationAdidas.PNG|thumb|right|200px|Generation Adidas official logo]] '''Generation Adidas''' is a joint venture between [[Major League Soccer]] and [[United States Soccer Federation|U.S. Soccer]] aimed at raising the level of young professional [[football (soccer)|soccer]] talent in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/story/354854/us-u-20-players-headline-2006-class|title=U.S. U-20 players headline 2006 class|author=|date=|website=ESPNFC.com}}</ref> The program, sponsored by [[Adidas]], offers professional-ready players in the U.S. developmental system not yet eligible for the [[MLS SuperDraft]] early entry, allowing MLS to compete with foreign professional clubs without comparable restrictions on player signing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ussoccerplayers.com/2010/01/mccabe-explains-generation-adidas.html|title=McCabe Explains Generation adidas|author=|date=|website=US Soccer Players}}</ref> From its establishment in 1997 to 2005, the program was sponsored by [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]] and was called '''Project-40'''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ussoccerplayers.com/resource_center/soccer_history/447766.html|title=US Soccer Players|author=|date=|website=www.ussoccerplayers.com}}</ref> Originally intended to improve the U.S. national team player pool, American national team eligibility is no longer required for program entry.
[[Carlos Parra]] was the first Project-40 player when he signed with the league and was allocated to the [[New York Red Bulls|New York/New Jersey MetroStars]] in 1997. Since then, the program has included players such as [[Tim Howard]], [[DaMarcus Beasley]], [[Maurice Edu]], [[Carlos Bocanegra]], [[Clint Dempsey]], [[Jozy Altidore]], [[Ben Olsen]], [[Sacha Kljestan]], [[Freddy Adu]], [[Brad Guzan]], [[Michael Bradley (soccer)|Michael Bradley]], [[Nick Rimando]] and [[Kyle Beckerman]].
Generation Adidas players do not count against the MLS senior roster and usually earn a much higher salary than the league minimum. Entering into the program automatically classifies a player as [[professional]], and thus disqualifies them from playing college soccer. As a result, Generation Adidas players are also guaranteed scholarships to continue their college education should their professional career not pan out.
From 1998 to 2000, MLS entered a team of Project-40 players, supplemented by other MLS players who did not get much playing time, into the [[USL First Division|A-League]] in the [[United Soccer Leagues|USL]].
In 2017, MLS introduced Canadian Generation Adidas players, part of a new initiative with the [[Canadian Soccer Association]]. Canadian Generation Adidas players count as domestic players on US based MLS teams.<ref>http://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2017/01/04/mls-announces-2017-generation-adidas-class-and-senior-signings</ref>
==Players== {{Expand list|date=August 2008}} Generation Adidas graduates are announced at the end of the MLS season (prior to 2008,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://usasoccer.blogspot.com/2009/09/graduating-from-generation-adidas.html|title=Graduating from Generation Adidas|publisher=USA Soccer|accessdate= 14 December 2012}}</ref> 2009,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theoriginalwinger.com/2009-11-23-mls-announces-the-graduation-of-generation-adidas-players|title=MLS Announces The Graduation Of Generation Adidas Players|publisher=The Original Winger|accessdate=14 December 2012}}</ref> 2010,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/generation-adidas-players-graduate-seasons-end|title=Generation adidas players to graduate at season's end|publisher=Major League Soccer|accessdate=14 December 2012}}</ref> and 2011<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wvhooligan.com/2011/11/22/12582/generation-adidas-graduates-for-2011/|title=Generation Adidas Graduates For 2011|publisher=WVHooligan|accessdate=14 December 2012}}</ref>) so in the charts below the graduation year represents the season after which the player was announced by MLS as a Generation Adidas graduate.
